ight of q[i] in bit order, but the prompt says 'Left' is q[i-1]. Let's follow the prompt's definition: Left = q[i-1], Right = q[i+1].\n         - q[0] neighbors: q[-1]=0 and q[1].\n         - q[511] neighbors: q[510] and q[512]=0.\n         - So `next_q[i] = q[i-1] ^ q[i+1]`.\n         - Using shifts: `next_q = (q << 1) ^ (q >> 1)`? \n           If q = ...q2, q1, q0. \n           q << 1 = ...q2, q1, q0, 0. (bit 0 is 0, bit 1 is q0, bit 2 is q1)\n           q >> 1 = 0, ...q2, q1. (bit 0 is q1, bit 1 is q2)\n           Actually: \n           q << 1 results in bit i being q[i-1].\n           q >> 1 results in bit i being q[i+1].\n           So `q_next = (q << 1) ^ (q >> 1)` is correct for the logic `q_next[i] = q[i-1] ^ q[i+1]` given the boundary conditions q[-1]=0 and q[512]=0.\n\n4. **Advice to avoid syntax errors**:\n   - Ensure the bit-width of `data` and `q` matches the spec (512 bits).\n   - Use `always @(posedge clk)` for sequential logic.\n   - Use `logic` for all signals to maintain SystemVerilog standards.\n   - Ensure the `load` signal is checked within the `always` block.\n   - Be careful with bit-shift boundaries; SystemVerilog shifts automatically handle zero-filling for logical shifts.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic             clk,\n    input  logic             load,\n    input  logic [511:0]    data,\n    output logic [511:0]    q\n);\n\n    // Internal register to hold the state\n    logic [511:0] q_reg;\n\n    // Initialize the register to zero to avoid starting with X\n    initial begin\n        q_reg = 512'b0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic for Rule 90 and Loading\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (load) begin\n            q_reg <= data;\n        end else begin\n            // Rule 90: q[i]'s next state is q[i-1] ^ q[i+1]\n            // q[i-1] is equivalent to shifting the whole vector left (q << 1)\n            // q[i+1] is equivalent to shifting the whole vector right (q >> 1)\n            // Boundary conditions: q[-1] = 0 and q[512] = 0 are handled by the zero-filling of shifts.\n            q_reg <= (q_reg << 1) ^ (q_reg >> 1);\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Drive the output\n    assign q = q_reg;\n\nendmodule"
